# Progress logging

Task planning lives **outside the repo** (GitHub Issues, vault, or other trackers). The repo keeps a single **daily engineering trail** under `doc/progress/` — narrative **and** command replay together.

## Layout (`doc/`)

```text
doc/
  PROGRESS_README.md       # Index + how to log; no session narrative
  progress/
    YYYY-MM-DD.md          # That day: narrative sections + NF replay blocks
  KNOWLEDGE_README.md      # Index to structured project_knowledge/
  project_knowledge/       # YAML registry (paths, runs, domain policies)
```

| Content | Belongs in |
|---------|------------|
| Engineering narrative, validation, blockers | `doc/progress/YYYY-MM-DD.md` — `##` sections |
| Verbatim `nextflow run` / long shell | Same daily file — `#### NF replay` blocks |
| Run-folder inventory, BAM/map paths, publish layout | `doc/project_knowledge/*.yaml` |
| AI behaviour, conda/screen policy | `.cursor/rules/` |
| Task backlog | **Outside repo** (GitHub Issues, vault) |

`PROGRESS_README.md` uses Obsidian wikilinks: `[[progress/2026-06-30]]` → `doc/progress/2026-06-30.md`.

**Deprecated (do not recreate):** `doc/TODO.md`, `doc/TODO_PROGRESS_LOG.md`, monolithic **`doc/NF_CMD.md`** (migrated into daily progress). Historical daily files may mention old paths — leave as audit trail.

## When to write (mandatory trigger: any progress)

Append to **today's** `doc/progress/YYYY-MM-DD.md` whenever the session produces progress — **not** only when code merges or issues close. Record:

- Code, migration, config, or rule changes
- Builds, tests, smoke runs, lint (`pass` / `fail` / `skipped`)
- **Investigation, diagnosis, conclusions** (even without code changes)
- Blockers, rollbacks, failed attempts
- Decisions or partial steps worth an audit trail
- **Nextflow / long shell runs** — include an **`#### NF replay`** block in the **same** daily file (same `##` section as the narrative when both exist)

## Narrative format

Each session slice gets one section:

```markdown
## YYYY-MM-DD — Short English title

- Plain-language bullets: intent, files touched, outcomes, follow-ups
```

Rules:

- **English** for all versioned text
- **Append only** — never delete or rewrite existing entries
- **No** mandatory field labels (`Date:`, `Files Changed:`, `Summary:` tables)
- **No** opaque IDs (`OPS-NF-001`, checklist section numbers)
- Supplements: `## YYYY-MM-DD — SUPP — topic`

## NF replay format (command blocks)

Use a **`#### NF replay`** subsection — the special marker for replayable commands. Wrap with HTML comments so nightly sync can extract blocks:

```markdown
## YYYY-MM-DD — PopDep chr36 smoke

- Goal: validate partial_router popdepth on chr36 …
- Outcome: exit 0, 12 succeeded

<!-- nf-replay -->
#### NF replay — main_raw_popdepth chr36

Working directory: `/data/home/tusr1/01projects/vmap4/10stats.genome/03run_…`. Outcome: exit 0.

```bash
source ~/.bashrc && conda activate run && \
screen -dmS popdep bash -lc 'source ~/.bashrc && conda activate run && cd … && nextflow run …'
```
<!-- /nf-replay -->
```

- One `#### NF replay` per distinct run attempt (or tightly related retry)
- Optional one-line **cwd / outcome** prose before the fenced `bash` block
- **Full** command lines inside the fence — no “see elsewhere”
- For run-only sessions (no code change), a standalone `## …` section containing only `#### NF replay` is fine
- Migrated history may use a trailing `## YYYY-MM-DD — NF replays` section; new entries should prefer inline blocks under the narrative `##` section

## New daily file

When creating `doc/progress/YYYY-MM-DD.md` for the first time:

1. Start with `# Progress — YYYY-MM-DD`
2. Add section(s) below
3. Prepend `[[progress/YYYY-MM-DD]]` to **Recent entries** in **`doc/PROGRESS_README.md`**
4. Keep roughly **14 days** in the index; drop older links (files stay on disk)

## Read policy

Agents **do not read** `doc/progress/` or `doc/PROGRESS_README.md` for task planning or “where is X?” facts — use **`doc/KNOWLEDGE_README.md`** and **`doc/project_knowledge/`** (workstation-core guardrail 14). Load progress logs only when the user explicitly asks for log archaeology or command replay.

## Project knowledge

Still update **`doc/project_knowledge/`** when registering new run folders or canonical resource paths — same session as the run when possible (see **session-to-agent-docs** skill). Use `nf_cmd_ref: doc/progress/YYYY-MM-DD.md — NF replay: <slug>` in YAML when a run is registered.
